<emphasis id="2D77ABCEAAC2E2D2287C9FA6BA0FC6F8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">Euphorbia carniolica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in the area between the Alps (north Italy, Switzerland) and the Eastern Carpathians and extends to Poland and Ukraine to the north (
<bibRefCitation id="7AD1FD38C6DBE9B85A848D248AF828E7" author="Smith, A. R." journalOrPublisher="Cambridge University Press, Cambridge" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7669322" refString="Smith, A. R., Tutin, T. G., 1968. Flora Europaea Vol. 2. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge" title="Flora Europaea Vol. 2" year="1968">Smith and Tutin 1968</bibRefCitation>
). It is considered as a Euro-Siberian element by 
<bibRefCitation id="53395AA3E59035F54915EC06D4F32868" author="Geltman, D. V." journalOrPublisher="Polish Botanical Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" pagination="147 - 161" refId="B7670918" refString="Geltman, D. V., 2015. Phytogeographical analysis of Euphorbia subgenus Esula (Euphorbiaceae). Polish Botanical Journal 60: 147 - 161" title="Phytogeographical analysis of Euphorbia subgenus Esula (Euphorbiaceae)" volume="60" year="2015">Geltman (2015)</bibRefCitation>
and an Illyricoid element by 
<bibRefCitation id="9E7B4FB2E12307F8916CE25651F4C8E8" author="Trinajstic, I." journalOrPublisher="Acta Botanica Croatica" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" pagination="135 - 142" refId="B7670111" refString="Trinajstic, I., 1992. A contribution to the phytogeographical classification of the Illyrian floral element. Acta Botanica Croatica 5: 135 - 142" title="A contribution to the phytogeographical classification of the Illyrian floral element" volume="5" year="1992">
<normalizedToken id="09E1F54686B50C73DB08C6D77AAD3EB5" originalValue="Trinajstić">Trinajstic</normalizedToken>
(1992)
</bibRefCitation>
, but its distribution justifies its placement to the south-east European elements. 
<normalizedToken id="80C1E0CFA26DB4B66657966E9C1EEE05" originalValue="Τhe">Τhe</normalizedToken>
populations in the central parts of the Balkans and Romania seem to be the closest to the newly-discovered, quite isolated Greek population. This first Greek record forms the southernmost limit of the 
<normalizedToken id="ABB7DDE8412F0E98411F8967E9BB5355" originalValue="species’">species'</normalizedToken>
distribution.
</paragraph>
